  "prompt": "What is indirect recursion?",
  "response": "Indirect recursion occurs when a function calls another function, which in turn calls the first function. This creates a cycle where the functions rely on each other to eventually reach a base case or termination condition. Indirect recursion can be contrasted with direct recursion, where a function directly calls itself.\n\nHere\u2019s a simple example to illustrate indirect recursion in Python:\n\n```python\ndef function_a(n):\n    if n > 0:\n        print(n)\n        function_b(n - 1)\n\ndef function_b(n):\n    if n > 0:\n        print(n)\n        function_a(n - 1)\n\n# Call the first function\nfunction_a(3)\n```\n\nIn this example, `function_a` calls `function_b`, and `function_b` calls `function_a`, creating an indirect recursive relationship. If you call `function_a(3)`, you will see a sequence of numbers printed from 3 down to 1 through these alternating calls.\n\nIndirect recursion can be useful for organizing complex algorithms or breaking down problems into smaller components, but it may also introduce additional complexity in understanding the flow of execution. Careful attention to base cases and termination conditions is essential to prevent infinite recursion.",
